A Comparative Evaluation of Metrics for Fast Mesh Simplification

Oliver Matias van Kaick, 
Hlio Pedrini, 
First published: 22 June 2006
https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-8659.2006.00935.x
Citations: 34
Sections
PDF
Tools
Share

Abstract

Triangle mesh simplification is of great interest in a variety of knowledge domains, since it allows manipulation and visualization of large models, and it is the starting point for the design of many multiresolution representations. A crucial point in the structure of a simplification method is the definition of an appropriate metric for guiding the decimation process, with the purpose of generating low error approximations at different levels of resolution. This paper proposes two new alternative metrics for mesh simplification, with the aim of producing high-quality results with reduced execution time and memory usage, and being simple to implement. A set of different established metrics is also described and a comparative evaluation of these metrics against the two new metrics is performed. A single implementation is used in the experiments, in order to enable the evaluation of these metrics independently from other simplification aspects. Results obtained from the simplification of a number of models, using the different metrics, are compared.

1. Introduction

High-fidelity surface models play an important role in several application fields, such as computer graphics, terrain modelling, scientific visualization and finite element methods. These applications usually involve the generation, manipulation and visualization of large amount of 3D spatial information.

Triangle meshes, because of their mathematical simplicity, have become a common standard in computer graphics. However, the development of new technologies that enable data collection at higher and higher resolutions, and the possibility of generating triangle meshes from a variety of computer graphics surface representations, have increased the complexity of these models, meaning that it is not possible to render or manipulate them at interactive rates.

Simplification of triangle meshes has helped to solve such problem, implying that a decimated mesh, generated from the original model and possessing less triangles, can be displayed and manipulated at interactive rates. Different approaches on how to simplify a triangle mesh have been proposed in the last years. One approach, proposed by Turk [1], is based on a global re-adjustment of mesh elements, where a new optimized and reduced triangulation that fits the data more adequately is created.

Other approach is based on the iterative application of local simplification operations, which modify a small portion of the mesh, reducing its complexity [2]. The most common operations are vertex elimination, edge collapse, face collapse and cell collapse. The currently well-established framework for this approach is to first assign a cost for each valid operation, which represents the amount of change introduced in the model. Then, the operation with minimum cost is applied, and the costs of the operations belonging to the modified mesh portion are recalculated. This iterative method continues until the desired resolution is achieved.

By recording the order in which these operations were applied, a multiresolution representation can be created. To obtain a triangle mesh with a desired level-of-detail, the operations are applied in accordance to the simplification record, until the requested resolution is achieved. The operation record can be simply linear [3,4], or defined according to a vertex hierarchy [58]. Employing such multiresolution approach implies that the quality of the model at intermediate levels of resolution depends entirely on the simplification method. The metric that guides this process is responsible for the overall quality of the multiresolution representation, indicating that a measure that generates the best results in terms of global error should be used.

On the other hand, since models of high complexity are becoming a common standard, and many applications require a fast simplification method, metrics should also aim at speed, preventing the usage of measures that evaluate the global maximum or mean errors of the model. Moreover, due to the development of different simplification methods in the last years, a fundamental task is to assess the quality of the approximations by means of comparative experiments [9].

Two new metrics for mesh simplification are proposed in this paper, with the purpose of generating low error approximations with reduced execution time and memory usage, and being simple to implement. The proposed metrics are compared against a set of different established metrics. A number of models are approximated using the different metrics, and the results are presented and discussed.

A single implementation is used in the experiments, with the aim of comparing the different metrics independently of other aspects related to the simplification method. A uniform framework is applied for the simplification of all models, and only the investigated metrics are changed from one experiment to other.

Some relevant previous works on simplification metrics are summarized in Section 2. Section 3 discusses the simplification measures that were investigated in this work and how the experiments were conducted. In Section 4, the discussed metrics are applied for the simplification of several data sets. Experimental results are presented and discussed. Finally, Section 5 concludes the paper with some final remarks.

2. Related Work

One of the first simplification methods, based on vertex removal, is proposed by Schroeder et al. [10]. A vertex is removed if the distance of the vertex to the average plane formed by its incident triangles exceeds a certain threshold. This error estimation is very simple to compute, but generates low-quality approximated models. The same occurs for vertex removal guided by the normal angle metric, proposed by Schrder and Rossbach [11]. The main characteristic of these simplification metrics is that they only use reduced information from the vertex neighbourhood.

The search for better quality model simplification led to the development of methods that allow precise error control, generating high quality results, but implying larger execution times. Hoppe [3] tracked simplification quality minimizing an energy function, which requires many vertex distance evaluations. Klein et al. [12] evaluated the Hausdorff distance between the original and simplified models, allowing precise error control, however, demanding large execution times despite the suggested optimizations for implementation.

Cohen et al. [13] indirectly restricted the maximum decimation error using simplification envelopes. Firstly, two additional meshes are created, the inner and outer envelopes, distanced from the original mesh by a certain threshold. Then, during the simplification method, it is verified if the application of a simplification operation does not cause the mesh to intersect with one of the envelopes. If that happens, the operation is not valid because the simplified model exceeded the possible maximum error, and the operation is reversed. At the end of this process, the simplified mesh necessarily satisfies tight error bounds.

Garland and Heckbert [14,15] proposed a quadric error metric for surface simplification, estimating the error introduced by a pair collapse operation as the distance from a vertex to a quadratic surface, represented as a symmetric matrix. Unlike the previous methods, that rely on precise global error tracking, quadrics are initialized only with information from the neighbourhood of a vertex, practically the same information used by the vertex distance or normal angle metrics. However, because the associated quadric surfaces adequately estimate the error introduced by the contraction of a mesh component, and because the quadric matrices are accumulated during the simplification process, they provide high-quality results.

The large quantity of memory required by the quadric metric, due to the storage of one symmetric matrix for each vertex (ten floating point values), led to the development of memoryless simplification by Lindstrom and Turk [16]. In this method, quadrics are also used to guide the simplification process, however, they are based on different constraints such as minimization of the error volume introduced by a simplification operation and optimization of triangle shape. Therefore, the method produces even better results than the original quadric metrics, in the mean error sense, although the matrices are not accumulated during the simplification.

Hussain et al. [17] proposed a metric that measures the amount of geometric change introduced by a simplification operation. This metric, combined with a value of vertex visual importance, produces results that are equivalent in terms of quality to the quadric metrics, showing that good approximations can also be achieved with the aid of simpler metrics.

Although metrics for view-dependent mesh refinement have been proposed and compared in other works [6,7,18], the main purpose of this comparative evaluation is to assess simplification metrics that reduce global error. The simplification metrics used in this comparative study are presented in the following section.

3. Simplification Method

In this section, the operation used for the simplification of the models in the experiments and the general simplification framework are first explained. Then, the studied metrics and the two proposed metrics are presented and discussed. Finally, it is shown how the global error of the approximations is evaluated.

In the following definitions, matrices are denoted in bold uppercase letters (M), vectors are in bold (n) and scalars are in plain format (a). A triangle mesh is composed of its geometry and its connectivity. The geometry is defined by the set of column vectors G={v1, v2,,vn}, where and n is the number of vertices in the mesh. The connectivity is constituted of a set of vertices V={1, 2,,n}, edges {i, j} and faces {i, j, k}, where i, j, kV. A vertex v is associated with the vector vv, which stores its geometric coordinates. The Euclidean vector norm is denoted ||. The triangles adjacent to a vertex v are denoted Tv.

3.1. Simplification operation

Half-edge collapse, illustrated in Figure 1, is employed for the simplification of the models during the experiments. This operation, characterized by the contraction of the oriented edge , maps the vertex i to the vertex j, removing the two triangles adjacent to the edge, denoted by Teij, which are degenerated during this operation. The other triangles incident to the removed vertex, denoted by TiTeij, are modified.

Edge contraction operations are the most finely graded, in a sense that they are the simpler modifications that can be applied to a mesh, and therefore allow a better error control. Specifically, the half-edge collapse operation was chosen for the experiments because it does not create new geometry [19], preserves topology and it is easy to implement.

The costs associated with the contraction of the two oriented edges and , which are related to the edge eij, are evaluated separately.

The order in which the half-edge collapses are applied is described in the next section, which outlines the employed simplification method.

3.2. Simplification Framework

In this work, triangle meshes are approximated according to the well-established simplification framework described in Luebke et al.[2]. Firstly, the costs of all candidate operations, in this case half-edge collapses that do not introduce degeneracies in the mesh, are calculated. The valid operations are inserted into a priority queue indexed by their costs. Thereafter, the iterative simplification procedure starts.

The operation on the top of the queue is applied, and the costs of all operations dependent on the modified mesh portion are updated, possibly causing the candidates to change positions in the priority queue. This procedure continues until a desired number of mesh faces is removed from the model.

The metrics used to assign a cost to the possible operations are described in the following section.

  • Volume quadric (VQ): the initial quadric for vertex v is initialized as in the quadric metric (QM), however, instead of using nt and dt of the plane equation of a triangle t, for this metric nt=vv1vv2+vv2vv3+vv3vv1 and dt=[vv1, vv2, vv3], where [] represents the triple product and (v1, v2, v3) are the vertices of triangle t[22]. This metric is named here volume quadric because it is based on the related work from Lindstrom and Turk [16], and the triple product also implies volume evaluation.

    The cost of a half-edge collapse is also computed as in the quadric metric (QM).

  • Memoryless volume quadric (MVQ): as originally proposed in [22], in this metric the volume quadric is not accumulated during the simplification method. After the cost for an operation is calculated, the quadrics associated with each vertex are simply discarded, not being stored for the next simplification iteration.

4. Experimental Results

Several models were used in the experiments, however, due to limited space, the results for only four models are presented in this work. The models are shown in Figure 3. Their characteristics are presented in Table 1. The experiments were performed on a PC Athlon XP 2000 MHz with 512 Mb RAM, running Linux operating system. A constraint to preserve the boundaries of the models was used in the simplification method.

Table 1. Model characteristics.
Model Vertices Faces
Bunny 35 947 69 451
Cow 2 904 5 804
Crater Lake 154 224 306 860
Turbine Blade 882 954 1 765 388

For error assessment, the MESH [23] program was employed, which calculates the Symmetric Hausdorff (ds) and the dRMSE distances between one model and its approximation, using different heuristics to accelerate the required calculations. This is a tool similar to the METRO program [24], widely applied to perform experiments that involve triangle mesh quality evaluation.

In Figure 4, twelve simplifications for the Cow Model are shown. The VD, NA, DC and SD metrics degenerate the model, while the other metrics provide visually good low-resolution approximations, preserving the most important features of the model. The same conclusions are suggested by the simplifications for the Bunny Model, shown in Figure 5. However, only the GE, GI, GV and QM metrics preserve small details of the Cow Model.

Figure 6 shows the distribution of the errors over the model surface for the simplifications of the Bunny Model presented in Figure 5. It can be seen that some metrics distribute the errors evenly across the surface, while other metrics generate higher errors in specific locations.

7-9 show the numerical results for the experiments, presenting the ds and dRMSE errors, and the execution time in relation to a percentage of the number of faces in the approximation. The ds and dRMSE errors are shown as a percentage of the bounding box diagonal that encompasses the test model. The error values for approximations possessing a specific number of faces are presented in Table 2.

The graphs on the left of Figure 7 show the dRMSE error metric for the simplification of the four models. Because the VD, NA, DC and SD metrics generate the results with lower quality, they are removed from the graphs shown on the right, which allow the detailed comparison between the selected metrics. It is evident that the best results are generated by the GV and QM metrics which are equivalent, presenting only small differences in terms of mean error. The other selected metrics also generate high-quality results.

Figure 8 shows graphs with the maximum error between the original models and their approximations. Although the results in terms of the ds error are not immediately clear as in the case of the dRMSE error, the former conclusions can also be achieved from these graphs, implying that the VD, NA, DC and SD metrics generate the approximations with lower quality, and the best results are obtained by the QM and GV metrics.

It can also be observed from the experiments that the geometric error simplification metric generates better results when combined with the error volume or when used without the combination with the vertex visual importance. The error volume metric generates better results than the quadrics based on volume.

Figure 9 shows the execution times for the simplification of the models according to each metric. The lower execution times are required by the metrics that store almost all error information in the quadric matrices (QM and VQ metrics), and by the DV and NA metrics, which are calculated using a small neighbourhood of the triangle mesh. The other metrics require higher execution times, since they calculate the simplification error extracting all necessary information from a triangle mesh portion.

However, their execution times are adequate when compared to metrics that calculate global error, and also because they do not use any extra memory or error accumulation, representing approximately the triple of the time required by the fastest metric investigated in this work.

Therefore, it can be concluded that although the GV and QM metrics are equivalent in terms of error, the QM metric should be used when a large amount of memory is available, since it enables fast simplification but requires storage of a symmetric matrix for each vertex of the model. On the other hand, the GV metric should be used for the simplification of large models or when only a small amount of memory is available, since it gives priority to the utilization of processing time in opposition to the utilization of significant memory amounts.

Although the VD and NA metrics generate approximations with many small irregularities, they preserve the overall shape of the models and require low execution times, implying that they are suitable for an initial simplification step. These two metrics could be adequate for rapidly generating a first approximation of a large model, which could then be refined by a more elaborated metric, for example.

On the other hand, the DC metric is not satisfactory because it always generates low-quality simplifications, since it is not possible to generate approximations that conform to a given error in terms of distance between two models using only curvature information. The SD metric, because of its effect of smoothing the meshes during simplification, also deforms extremely the models.

The EV metric presents a good ratio between the quality of the approximations and the required execution times, being suitable for applications that require fast and memoryless simplification, but generating approximations with considerable quality.

5. Conclusions

This paper proposed two new metrics for mesh simplification, with the aim of producing high-quality results with reduced execution time and low memory usage. A comparative evaluation of these new metrics against a set of different established metrics was also presented. From the results of the experiments, it can be concluded that it is possible to generate high-quality approximations for triangle meshes without storing any extra information during the simplification method, therefore using less memory and reduced processing time.
